0.1 Preliminaries

1 Task 1: Data Source

This dataset is provided to me by Carrie Hersh, DO, staff neurologist at Cleveland Clinic Lou Ruvo Center for Brain Health. It is an existing database of patients with multiple sclerosis who were treated at Cleveland Clinic Mellen Center with either Dimenthyl Fumarate or Fingolimod. The original retrospective observational study comparing the efficacy both the two disease-modifying therapies was published in Mult Scler Relat Disord. 2016 Nov;10:44-52. (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27919497). The subset of data used for my project 1 analysis is comprised of baseline patient demographics, radiographic and clinical disease measures.

In the proj1.csv file, there are baseline data of 659 patients with relapsing multiple sclerosis whose data were collected via electronic medical record system after instutional review board approval. Baseline information prior to being prescribed either Dimethryl Fumarate or Fingolimod were collected - these include patient demographics, disease characteristics such as duration, type, various radiographic such as lesion burden, brain parenchymal fraction, and clinical markers such as disability scores and performance scores are measured and collected.

ms <- proj1 %>%
  rename(prior_drugs=prior_.drugs) %>%
  mutate(id = as.character(subject_id),
         age = as.numeric(age),
         dd=as.numeric(disease_duration),
         base_gde_c = as.integer(base_gde_c),
         base_relapse_c = as.integer(base_relapse_c),
         prior_drugs = as.integer(prior_drugs),
         sex = factor(sex,
                      levels=c(0,1),
                      labels=c("Female","Male")),
         race = factor(racen,
                       levels=c(1,2,3),
                       labels=c("White","Black", "Other")),
         ms_type = factor(ms_type,
                          levels=c(0,1),
                          labels=c("Relapsing MS","Other MS")),
         jcv = factor(jcvirus_ab, 
                      levels=c(0,1,4),
                      labels=c("Negative", "Positive", "Not Tested")),
         base_assist=factor(base_assist, 
                            levels=c(0, 1,2),
                            labels=c("Independent", "Cane", "Walker")),
         base_new_t2=factor(base_new_t2, 
                            levels=c(0,1),
                            labels=c("No T2 Lesion", "T2 Lesions")),
         base_dis = ifelse(base_assist == "Independent", 
                                  "Mild disability", "Moderate-Severe Disability"),
         base_relapse = as.factor(ifelse(base_relapse_c > 0, 
                                         "Relapse", "No Relapse")), 
         base_gde = as.factor(ifelse(base_gde_c > 0, 
                                     "No Gad+ Lesions", "Gad+ Lesions"))) %>%
  select(id, age, sex, dd, race, ms_type, jcv, prior_drugs, base_wbc, base_assist, base_new_t2, base_dis, base_relapse, base_relapse_c, base_gde, base_gde_c, base_BPF, base_T2LV)

First, I have changed integer variables such as age and disease dureation in to continuous numeric variables.
Then I changed the numeric variables into its corresponding factors, this includes sex, race, ms_type, jvc, base_assist, base_new_t2.
Finally, I created additional binary factors from existing multi-categorical factor variables. base_dis is based on base_assist, if a patient is categorized as Independent in base_assist, then this patient will be categorized as Mild disability. All other factor levels in base_assist will be categorized as Moderate-Severe Disability in base_dis. If a patient have 1 or more MS relapses at baseline as indicated in base_relapse_c, then this patient will be categorized as Relapse in base_relapse, patients with 0 relapses baseline in base_relapse_c will be categorized as No Relapse in base_relapse. Similarly, patients who have 0 gadolinium enhancing lesions in base_gde_c will be categorized as No Gad+ Lesions in base_gde, and patients who have 1 or more gadolinium enhancing lesions in base_gde_c will be categorizes as Gad+ Lesions in base_gde.

Since this is an observational study, I expect many of the variables will contain missing values since it is not the standard clinical practice to obtain values for all the baseline variables included in this study. To check missing values in this dataset, I have listed the table below indicating the number of NAs in each column

map_df(ms, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))

It is conclude from this output that:

  • dd is missing in 7 subjects
  • prior_drugs is missing in 8 subjects
  • jcv is missing in 9 subjects
  • base_wbc is missing in 71 subjects
  • base_assist and corresponding derived binary variable base_dis are missing in 40 subjects
  • base_new_t2 missing in 18 subjects
  • base_relapse_c and corresponding derived binary variable base_relapse are missing in 14 subjects
  • base_gde_c and corresponding derived binary variable base_gde are missing in 28 subjects
  • base_BPF is missing in 251 subjects
  • base_T2LV is missing in 269 subjects

The rest of the variables dont have any missing data

Since there are quite a few subjects with missing data and they may influence the final outcome analysis. It is possible that those values simply werent routine collected at time determiend as baseline prior to starting the studied medication, I will assume the values are missing at random for the remainder of the analysis. I will perform simple imputation as follows: for continuous variables, I will perform simple imputation based on age, sex, race, and ms_type; for non-continuous integers, I will perform simple imputation based on predictive mean matching on the bases of age, sex, race and ms_type; for categorical variables, I will replace with the mode for that variable (calculated in r).

Another tibble is then created with the derived variables based on imputed data.

ms1 <- imp.1 %>%
  mutate(base_dis = as.factor(ifelse(base_assist == "Independent", 
                                  "Mild disability", "Moderate-Severe Disability")),
         base_relapse = as.factor(ifelse(base_relapse_c > 0, 
                                         "Relapse", "No Relapse")), 
         base_gde = as.factor(ifelse(base_gde_c > 0, 
                                     "No Gad+ Lesions", "Gad+ Lesions"))) %>%
  select(id, age, sex, dd, race, ms_type, jcv, prior_drugs, base_wbc, base_assist, base_new_t2, base_dis, base_relapse, base_relapse_c, base_gde, base_gde_c, base_BPF, base_T2LV)

5 Task 5: My Subjects

This data describe 659 patients selected for this retropsepctive observational study. Inclusion criteria includes patients with multiple sclerosis followed at Cleveland Clinic Mellen Center who were started on either Dimenthyl Fuamarate between 03/2013 to 07/2013 or Fingolimod between 10/2010 and 08/2011, in addition, they must have available data from 12-month follow up visit. Brain parenchymal fraction and T2 lesion volume data were obtained via automated segmentation methods after publishing date.

6 Task 6: My Variables

There are 18 variables in the ms1 data set.
  1. id is subject id ranging from 1 to 659
  2. age is subjects age at baseline, in years.
  3. sex indicates whether subject is male (0) or female (1).
  4. dd is the subjects disease duration at time of study baseline, in years.
  5. race is the race of the subjects, 1=white, 2=black, 3=other.
  6. ms_type indicates subtypes ofMS, 1=relapsing ms (PP), 2=other ms (SP).
  7. jcv indicates the results of JC Virus antibody results at baseline, JCV positivity confers higher risk for developing progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy. 0 = negative, 1 = positive, 4 = not performed
  8. prior_drugs lists the total number of disease modifying therapies the subject has tried in the past prior to switching to the drug of interest in this study.
  9. base_wbc is the baseline white blood cell count, in thousands.
  10. base_assist indicates the subjects functional capacity at baseline, whether ambulating independently (0), needing a cane (1), or needing a walker (2)
  11. base_dis is a binary variable derived from base_assist, indepdent is categorized as mild disability, while use of walker and cane are categorized as moderate to severe disability.
  12. base_new_t2 is a binary variable indicating whether there are any new T2-weighted MRI MS lesions at baseline (0=no new T2 lesion, 1=new T2 lesion)
  13. base_relapse_c lists the total number of relapses a subject has had by time of switching to drug of interest in this study
  14. base_relapse is a binary variable derived from base_relapse_c indicating no history of relapse at baseline, or history of relapses at baseline.
  15. base_gde_c lists the total number of gadolinium enhancing MS lesions a subject has had by time of switching to drug of interest in this study
  16. base_gde is a binary variable derived from base_gde_c indicating no history of gadolinium enhancing lesions at baseline, or history of gadolinium enhancing lesions at baseline.
  17. base_BPF is the calculated brain parenchymal fraction base on MRI. This is defined as the ratio of total volume of brain parenchymal to the total volume within the brain surface, ranges from 0 to 1. Patients who have brain atrophy, the ratio is expected to be smaller than somebody without MS.
  18. base_T2LV is the calculated total volume of T2-weighted MRI lesions, in ml.

7 Task 7: My Planned Linear Regression Model

I will predict brain parenchymal fraction base_BPF using some combination of the following variables

  • age - quantitative
  • sex - binary
  • dd - quantitative
  • race - multi-categorical
  • ms_type - binary
  • jcv - multi-categorical
  • prior_drugs - multicategorical
  • base_relapse_c - quantitative
  • base_gde_c - quantitative

Since bpf measures brain atrophy, which is accelrated by normal aging and high MS disease activity I predict that age and dd will have high predictive values on bpf. Other indicators of disease activity, such as prior_drugs (patients with more severe disease likely to have tried more drugs) and base_relapse_c (higher number of relapses indicate more active disease) likely will also have significant predictive value.

plot(spearman2(base_BPF ~ age + sex + dd + race + ms_type + jcv + prior_drugs + base_relapse_c + base_gde_c, data = ms1))

A Spearman 2 plot of my predictors indicate that age pack the most predictive punch for a non-linear term, followed by sex, dd, and ms_type.

8 Task 8: My Planned Logistic Regression Model

I will predict level of disability, base_dis, using some combination of the following variables:

  • age - quantitative
  • sex - binary
  • dd - quantitative
  • race - multi-categorical
  • ms_type - binary
  • prior_drugs - multicategorical
  • base_relapse_c - quantitative
  • base_new_t2 - binary
  • base_gde_c - quantitative
  • base_T2LV - quantitative

I predict that indicators of more active or severe disease, such as dd, base_relapse_c, base_new_t2, base_gde_c, and base_T2LV most likely will have more predictive value.

plot(spearman2(base_dis ~ age + sex + dd + race + ms_type + jcv + prior_drugs + base_relapse_c + base_gde_c, data = ms1))

However, the Spearman 2 plot suggests that ms_type is actually the variable with most predictive punch, followed weakly by dd, age, and prior_drugs. The remaining variables do not seem to pack much predictive punch in predicting base_dis.

9 Task 9: Affirmation

  1. The data set contains 659 observations on 18 variables.
  2. Although the variables with most missing data, base_BPF and base_T2LV have nearly a third of the subjects with missing values, this still leaves me more than the minimum requirement of 100 with complete data. I will, however, perform rest of the analysis using simply imputed data for completeness.
  3. There are multiple types of outcomes considered. One quantitative is base_BPF, which is a continuous numerical variable as measure of brain atrophy. The other outcome is binary base_dis, which is converted from its numerical outcome into categories with functional status of mild disability and moderate to severe disability.
  4. I have multiple regression input candidates to use in my model. Some quantitative variables such as age and dd, some binary variables such as sex and base_new_t2, and some multi-categorical variables such as race and jcv.

Since this is a dataset derived from previously published work. All patient identifiers ahve been removed. I am certain that it is completely appropriate for these data to be shared with anyone, without any conditions. There are no concerns about privacy or security.

10 Task 10: Linear Regression

Based on the spearman plot listed in task 7, I will compare the following two models:

Model1: a, ols model with limited predictive variables (only including the ones with adjusted p2 above 0.10, which are sex, dd, and ms_type), and a non-linear restricted cubic spline with 3 knots for age.

Model2: an ols model with all the predictors, since I have a sample size of 659, there is enough room to spend a few extra DFs

There is no issue of colinearity here as suggested by relatively small VIF scores.
